<DOC><DOCNO> AP880715-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 2343EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-Tornadoes     07-15 0370</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Tornadoes,0381</SECOND><HEAD>Dozens Injured, 100 Homes Damaged By Tornadoes</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto AH4</HEAD><BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Massive thunderstorms packing tornadoes andwind gusts up to 92 mph slammed into Omaha and Council Bluffs,Iowa, on Friday, injuring at least 40 people and damaging more than100 homes.   One tornado uprooted trees, downed power lines, started firesand overturned railroad cars in a 2-mile stretch in western CouncilBluffs along Interstate 29 and the Missouri River, which dividesthe two cities.   Most of Council Bluffs' 60,000 residents were without powerFriday night and the situation was not expected to change throughmorning, said Matt Daunis of Iowa Power and Light Co.   Council Bluffs Mayor Tom Hanafan ordered a curfew from 10 p.m.to dawn to guard against looting. Members of the Iowa NationalGuard patroled the streets.   An Omaha man was reported in critical condition with neck andpossible internal injuries after a tree crashed onto the roof ofhis car. Most other injuries were minor, said officials of threehospitals who counted a total of 40 people treated forstorm-related injuries.   Exits off Interstate 29 into Council Bluffs were closed and theIowa Highway Patrol sealed off the area most heavily damaged.   Possible tornadoes and funnel clouds were reported throughoutthe Omaha area as hail fell and more than 2 inches of rain causedstreet flooding.   ``We went to the hallway and we were praying very hard,'' saidCouncil Bluffs resident Lu Guzenhauser, who was baby-sitting fortwo children when the storm hit her neighborhood.   Ms. Guzenhauser and the children were not injured. However, partof the tool shed behind her house was hanging from power lines inthe front of her home after the storm.   Trees as thick as 48 inches in diameter snapped in half inCouncil Bluffs and others as tall as 100-feet were uprooted atDodge Park Golf Course in Omaha.   In the worst 2-mile stretch in Council Bluffs, the tops ofhundreds of trees were sawed off by the twister, sidewalks wereuplifted and roofs were blown off houses.   A wind gust of 92 mph was reported at Omaha's Eppley Airfield at4:21 p.m., the National Weather Service reported.</TEXT></DOC>